WEBVTT

00:03.473 --> 00:07.919
Gordon Volkman was one of these people.

00:11.323 --> 00:26.243
We were interested in the fact that reflectivity 
from the bottom is going to be disturbed by the

00:11.323 --> 00:26.243
shape of the bottom. And it became apparent that If 
the bottom was sloped, the reflections from the

00:31.334 --> 00:38.703
bottom would appear to come in from a different 
direction. Also, if one was looking down the ridge

00:40.225 --> 00:48.976
of a mountain range, one would be in a shadow zone 
for bottom reflected sound. If one was looking

00:49.056 --> 00:57.747
down a valley, one would be in a sound channel from 
the standpoint of reflected sound.

00:58.503 --> 01:21.912
simple result of this kind of thinking, which 
wasn't really very fundamental thinking, but it

00:58.503 --> 01:21.912
was important to start thinking this way, was that 
every spot on the ocean has its own directivity

00:58.503 --> 01:21.912
index

00:58.503 --> 01:21.912
for bottom reflected sound, so that both the 
intensities and directions could change a great

00:58.503 --> 01:21.912
deal upon the bottom configuration.

01:29.671 --> 01:58.463
Also, another aspect of underwater sound, in 
which a great deal of field work was done, both with

01:29.671 --> 01:58.463
the standpoint of research work and also with the 
possibility of working with aviators, was that it

01:29.671 --> 01:58.463
quickly appeared one one night that if the source 
was at the bottom, near the bottom of the ocean, in

01:59.641 --> 02:25.716
fact, if it was at a depth in which, if the water was 
deep and it was at a depth at which the sound

01:59.641 --> 02:25.716
velocity equaled the velocity near the surface, 
that about 20 miles, 15 to 20 miles away, there

01:59.641 --> 02:25.716
would be a very strong convergence zone. And what 
was at least as important was that at all ranges out

02:28.261 --> 02:41.978
to that range,

02:28.261 --> 02:41.978
near-surface targets would be in the direct path. 
So this was called the Reliable Acoustic Path.

02:49.588 --> 02:58.099
Actually, it was the Naval Research Laboratory 
people who gave it that name and did some excellent

02:49.588 --> 02:58.099
work on it. But this was sort of a new concept in our 
game. It opened up the possibility of having

03:03.995 --> 03:10.785
much deeper towed sonar. It had the possibility of 
instrumentation, bottom mounted

03:11.626 --> 03:22.341
instrumentation, in which we could listen to it. 
If we were in deep water, we could listen to it out to

03:22.722 --> 03:27.529
a range of 20 miles. out to a range of 10 miles, it 
would get weaker and weaker, and then it would

03:28.353 --> 03:33.461
start getting stronger and stronger. So this 
opened up

03:34.002 --> 03:42.134
the range of things that could be done 
acoustically in the ocean a great deal. It was

03:43.616 --> 03:52.690
another step in showing that if one was willing to 
be more special purpose in the way one utilized

03:43.616 --> 03:52.690
acoustics, then the ocean was a more benign place 
than was usually given credit for. Let's shut it

03:58.320 --> 04:06.090
off a

